      {
        "node": {
          "text": "Hell yeah🔥\n\n📌Comment “WANT” or tap the link in bio for product links.\n\n(Please DM us for credit or removal)\n#creed #creedband #scottstapp #divorceddadrock #postgrunge\n\n“My Own Prison” by Creed isn’t just a debut single—it’s a statement of identity.\n\nReleased as the title track of their first album, My Own Prison, the song captures everything that would define Creed’s sound: heavy, brooding guitar riffs, a slow-burning atmosphere, and the unmistakable voice of Scott Stapp delivering lyrics that feel both personal and spiritual.\n\nAt its core, “My Own Prison” is about guilt, redemption, and being trapped within your own mind. The imagery is dark—almost biblical—painting a picture of judgment and isolation, but also a quiet search for forgiveness. It’s not just about religion; it’s about consequences, self-reflection, and the weight of your own actions. What makes the track stand out is its restraint. It doesn’t rush. It builds slowly, letting every word and note sink in, creating a haunting mood that stays with you long after it ends. It feels less like a song and more like a confession set to music. Even years later, “My Own Prison” remains one of the most powerful introductions any rock band has ever made—raw, atmospheric, and unapologetically honest."
        }
      }
    ]
  },
